[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.6: Python Implementation Example
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Heads up:** This is a deliberately simple, illustrative implementation of the pseudocode walkthrough from Recipe 11.6. It shows one way you could translate the symptom-checker triage-bot pipeline into working Python using boto3 against Amazon Bedrock (LLM with function-calling), Amazon Bedrock Knowledge Bases (managed RAG over the clinical-protocol corpus), Amazon Bedrock Guardrails, AWS Lambda, Amazon API Gateway, Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon S3, and Amazon EventBridge. The demo uses a `MockBedrockRuntime` standing in for LLM-driven question phrasing and structured response generation, a `MockEHR` standing in for the chart-context system, a `MockKnowledgeBase` standing in for the clinical-protocol corpus retrieval, a `MockClinicalRuleEngine` standing in for the deterministic clinical-decision-rule library (HEART, Wells, Centor, Ottawa), a `MockNurseLine` standing in for the nurse-line escalation system, a `MockTelehealthScheduler` standing in for the telehealth-booking system, a `MockUrgentCareDirectory` standing in for the urgent-care lookup, a `MockTable` for each DynamoDB table (conversation-state, conversation-metadata, tool-call-ledger, triage-decision-record-journal, protocol-version-registry, outcome-correlation-pending), a `MockEventBus` for EventBridge, a `MockDecisionJournal` standing in for the S3 triage-decision-record archive, and a `MockCloudWatch` for the metric emissions. It is not production-ready. There is no real Bedrock Agents action group configured, no real Knowledge Base ingestion, no real Guardrail configuration, no API Gateway plumbing, no WAF rule tuning, no per-Lambda IAM least privilege, no KMS customer-managed keys, no VPC endpoints to the EHR or nurse-line systems, no Object-Lock-protected decision-record journal, no Connect contact-center handoff, no SageMaker-hosted emergency-screening classifier, and no Secrets Manager wiring for the upstream-system credentials. Think of it as the sketchpad version: useful for understanding the shape of a triage-bot AI pipeline that respects the input-screening discipline, the continuous-emergency-screening discipline, the chart-context-loading discipline, the protocol-corpus-as-code discipline, the citation-grounding discipline, the conservative-bias-default discipline, the clinical-decision-rule-as-deterministic-tool discipline, the nurse-line-escalation-as-first-class-capability discipline, and the audit-everything discipline this recipe demands. It is not something you would point at a health system's patient app on Monday morning. Consider it a starting point, not a destination.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > The code maps to the nine pseudocode steps from the main recipe: receive the message, bootstrap the session, run input safety screening with continuous-emergency-screening (Step 1); load the patient's chart context (Step 2); identify the presenting symptom and select the protocol (Step 3); conduct the structured protocol-driven questioning (Step 4); compute clinical-decision rules where the protocol calls for them (Step 5); compute the acuity recommendation with conservative-bias enforcement (Step 6); run output safety screening with citation verification and conservative-bias verification (Step 7); persist the durable triage-decision record alongside the conversation log (Step 8); close the conversation and archive the audit record (Step 9). The synthetic patients, protocols, clinical-decision-rule scores, and recommendations in the demo are fictional; nothing in this file should be interpreted as clinical guidance from any real institution.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Setup
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m You will need the AWS SDK for Python:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```bash
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m pip install boto3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In production you would also configure an Amazon Bedrock Agent (or a custom Lambda-based orchestrator) with action groups defining the triage tools (`chart_context_lookup`, `intent_classify`, `emergency_screen`, `protocol_select`, `protocol_retrieve`, `clinical_rule_compute`, `recommendation_compose`, `nurse_line_escalate`, `telehealth_book`, `urgent_care_locate`, `outcome_correlation_queue`), each backed by a tool-implementation Lambda that wraps the institution's EHR, clinical-protocol library, clinical-decision-rule engine, nurse-line system, telehealth scheduler, and urgent-care directory. You would also configure an Amazon Bedrock Knowledge Base ingesting curated content from S3 covering the institution-validated triage protocols (Schmitt-Thompson Adult, Schmitt-Thompson Pediatric, or institutional adaptations), the clinical-decision-rule reference content, the institutional regulatory-disclosure phrasings, and the patient-facing instruction templates, with metadata-filtered retrieval scoped to protocol_id, protocol_version, decision_point_id, pediatric_vs_adult, and special_population_flags. You would configure an Amazon Bedrock Guardrail with restricted-topic filters for diagnosis-attempted, treatment-recommendation-attempted, drug-prescription-attempted, and off-protocol-clinical-claim categories at minimum, an API Gateway endpoint fronting the chat-handler Lambda, an AWS WAF web ACL with rate limits tuned for the triage pattern (patients in distress sometimes type rapidly; rate limits should not block legitimate fast-typing), the six DynamoDB tables (conversation-state, conversation-metadata, tool-call-ledger, triage-decision-record-journal, protocol-version-registry, outcome-correlation-pending), an Amazon S3 bucket with Object Lock in compliance mode for the triage-decision-record journal sized to the longest of HIPAA's six-year minimum, the state's medical-record retention rules (often 7-10+ years for adult records, sometimes longer for pediatric records), FDA SaMD post-market obligations where applicable, and the institutional regulatory floor, an EventBridge bus for triage-lifecycle events (`conversation_started`, `protocol_selected`, `emergency_screened`, `recommendation_computed`, `recommendation_delivered`, `escalation_triggered`, `outcome_correlation_completed`, `conversation_closed`), a Kinesis Data Firehose delivery stream for the conversation-audit archive, AWS Secrets Manager secrets for the EHR, nurse-line, telehealth, and urgent-care-directory credentials, and (where applicable) the Connect contact-center integration for the live nurse-line handoff path. The demo replaces all of these with small mocks so the focus stays on the per-turn input-screening, continuous-emergency-screening, chart-context-loading, protocol-selection, protocol-driven questioning, clinical-decision-rule computation, conservative-bias-aware recommendation logic, output-screening, and decision-record-persistence logic rather than on the platform plumbing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Your environment needs credentials configured (via environment variables, an instance profile, or `~/.aws/credentials`). The IAM role or user needs:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `bedrock:InvokeModel` for the orchestration model and the intent-classification model
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `bedrock-agent-runtime:InvokeAgent` if you wire Bedrock Agents instead of running the orchestration in a custom Lambda
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `bedrock:Retrieve` and `bedrock:RetrieveAndGenerate` on the Knowledge Base ARN holding the clinical-protocol corpus
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `bedrock:ApplyGuardrail` on the Guardrail ARN you configured
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `dynamodb:GetItem`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:UpdateItem`, `dynamodb:Query` on the six tables, scoped to the specific table ARNs
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `events:PutEvents` on the triage-events bus
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `firehose:PutRecord` on the audit-archive Firehose delivery stream
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `s3:PutObject` on the triage-decision-record-journal bucket prefix
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `cloudwatch:PutMetricData` for operational metrics (resolution rate per protocol, escalation rate per protocol, time-to-recommendation, citation-coverage rate, conservative-bias-compliance rate, tool-call success per tool, per-cohort slices)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `secretsmanager:GetSecretValue` on the upstream-system credential secrets pinned to the current rotation versions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - `kms:Decrypt` and `kms:GenerateDataKey` on the customer-managed keys protecting the conversation tables, the tool-call ledger, the decision-record table, the protocol-version-registry table, the decision-record journal, the audit archive, and the Secrets Manager secrets
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - For the tool Lambdas calling the EHR, nurse-line, telehealth scheduler, or urgent-care directory: VPC-endpoint or PrivateLink permissions, plus whatever each upstream system's auth flow requires
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Scope each Lambda's IAM role to the specific resource ARNs it touches. The tutorial-level permissions above are fine for learning and will fail any serious IAM review. The chat-handler Lambda has Bedrock invocation and read-write on the conversation tables, but no direct access to the EHR or the nurse-line system. The chart-context-lookup Lambda has read-only access to the EHR resources it needs. The clinical-rule-compute Lambdas have no external-system access (pure compute). The nurse-line-escalate Lambda has the access required to post handoff events to the nurse-line system. None of the bot's Lambdas have write access to the clinical record; the bot is read-only with respect to clinical data. Separation of concerns by Lambda role limits the blast radius of any single Lambda's compromise. Avoid wildcard actions and resources in production.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things worth knowing upfront:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The clinical-protocol corpus is the bot.** The code below assumes the institution's triage protocols (whether licensed Schmitt-Thompson, an institutional adaptation, or institution-built) are curated, dated, version-controlled, and chunked with metadata for protocol_id, protocol_version, decision_point_id, pediatric_vs_adult, special_population_flags, and effective_date. Building the corpus is the project. Skip the corpus work and the bot answers questions from the LLM's parametric memory rather than from the institution's protocol, which is exactly the failure mode the architecture exists to prevent. The `PROTOCOL_LIBRARY` placeholder in the config is where you wire in your real corpus (in production this is the Knowledge Base index plus a structured protocol-runtime, not a Python dict).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Continuous emergency screening is non-negotiable.** Every patient utterance runs through the screening layer, not just the first. A patient who starts with a vague concern and then mid-conversation reveals "actually I am bleeding heavily" or "I lost feeling in my legs" needs immediate emergency routing regardless of where the conversation was. The demo's `_emergency_screen` implements this; production layers a tuned classifier on top.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Conservative-bias enforcement is the policy floor.** The protocols are designed with conservative bias; the bot's logic enforces it. When the bot is uncertain at any step, when the protocol-driven and rule-driven recommendations diverge, when the patient's responses are ambiguous, the recommendation defaults to the higher acuity (or escalates to a nurse). The demo's `_apply_conservative_bias` and `_verify_conservative_bias` implement this; production has the policy documented, reviewed by compliance, and audited in the quality-review process.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Clinical-decision rules run as deterministic code, not LLM math.** The HEART, Wells, Centor, and Ottawa rules compute structured scores from structured inputs. The LLM does this poorly. The demo's `clinical_rule_compute_tool` follows the deterministic pattern; production runs each rule as its own Lambda with version stamps and validation reports.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Citation grounding is architectural floor.** Every recommendation cites the protocol it was based on, the protocol version, the decision points within the protocol, and any clinical-decision rules used. The output safety screening verifies the grounding before delivery. The audit record preserves the citation trail. Skip the grounding and the bot produces ungrounded recommendations that look authoritative, which is the failure mode that gets institutions sued and patients hurt.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The bot does not commit the institution to a clinical decision.** The bot's recommendations are informational triage routing; the actual clinical evaluation happens at the recommended care level. The system prompt and the output-screening filters enforce this scope; diagnosis-attempted and treatment-recommendation-attempted language is replaced with the safer informational template.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Conversation logs are dense PHI plus may include sensitive disclosures.** Patients in triage may disclose mental-health crisis, intimate-partner violence, child or elder abuse, sexual-health concerns, substance use, and other topics covered by mandatory-reporting laws. The audit, retention, access-control, and downstream-clinical-workflow story has to handle each of these with statutory awareness. The demo writes a redacted record; production writes through Firehose into an Object-Lock S3 bucket sized to the longest of HIPAA's six-year minimum, the state's medical-record retention rules, FDA SaMD post-market obligations where applicable, and the institutional regulatory floor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **DynamoDB rejects Python `float`.** Every confidence score, threshold, clinical-rule score, and numeric metadata field passes through `Decimal` on its way in and on its way out. The `_to_decimal` helper handles it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The example collapses many Lambdas into a single Python file.** In production the chat handler, the input-screening function, the continuous-emergency-screening function, the chart-context-loading function, each clinical-rule-compute function, the protocol-retrieval function, the recommendation-compose function, the output-screening function, the nurse-line-escalation function, the decision-record-persistence function, and the audit-archival function are separate Lambdas with their own IAM roles, error handling, retries, and DLQs. Comments call out where the boundaries should fall.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Configuration and Constants
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Everything that is configuration rather than logic lives here. Resource names, model IDs, the protocol library, the clinical-decision-rule registry, the emergency-screen vocabulary, and the validation thresholds are what you would change between environments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import logging
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import re
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import uuid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from collections import defaultdict
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from datetime import datetime, timedelta, timezone
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from decimal import Decimal
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from typing import Optional
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m import boto3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m from botocore.config import Config
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Structured logging. In production, ship JSON-formatted records
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # to CloudWatch Logs Insights for cross-call investigation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Conversation logs are dense PHI: patient symptom descriptions,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # medication mentions, mental-health disclosures, family
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # history, and identifiers can all surface in a triage chat.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Log structural metadata only (session_id, intent, tool name,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # tool latency, tool outcome, protocol_id, protocol_version),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # never raw user utterances, never raw generated responses,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # never tool arguments that contain identifiers, never specific
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # clinical-rule input values. The full transcripts and full
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # tool calls live in the audit pipeline (Firehose plus
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Object-Lock S3) with appropriate access controls.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m logger.setLevel(logging.INFO)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Adaptive retry handles throttling from Bedrock, DynamoDB,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # EventBridge, Firehose, CloudWatch, S3, and Secrets Manager.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # The triage-bot response window is tighter than most member-
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # facing bots: a patient in distress needs a fast turn, but
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # fast-and-wrong is worse than slow-and-right for high-acuity
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # protocols.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG = Config(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     retries={"max_attempts": 3, "mode": "adaptive"})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Module-level clients. Reused across Lambda invocations in
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # warm containers so each invocation does not pay the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # connection cost.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m REGION = "us-east-1"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m bedrock_runtime       = boto3.client("bedrock-runtime",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m bedrock_agent_runtime = boto3.client("bedrock-agent-runtime",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m dynamodb              = boto3.resource("dynamodb",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m eventbridge_client    = boto3.client("events",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m firehose_client       = boto3.client("firehose",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m cloudwatch_client     = boto3.client("cloudwatch",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m s3_client             = boto3.client("s3",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m secrets_client        = boto3.client("secretsmanager",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      region_name=REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                      config=BOTO3_RETRY_CONFIG)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Resource Names ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Fill these in with your actual resource names. The demo
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # prints what it would write rather than failing if the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # resources do not exist; see run_demo() at the bottom.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CONVERSATION_STATE_TABLE        = "triage-bot-conversation-state"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CONVERSATION_METADATA_TABLE     = "triage-bot-conversation-metadata"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m TOOL_CALL_LEDGER_TABLE          = "triage-bot-tool-call-ledger"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m DECISION_RECORD_TABLE           = "triage-bot-decision-record-journal"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m PROTOCOL_VERSION_REGISTRY_TABLE = "triage-bot-protocol-version-registry"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m OUTCOME_CORRELATION_TABLE       = "triage-bot-outcome-correlation-pending"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m TRIAGE_EVENT_BUS_NAME           = "triage-bot-events-bus"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m AUDIT_ARCHIVE_FIREHOSE_NAME     = "triage-bot-audit-archive"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m DECISION_RECORD_BUCKET          = "triage-bot-decision-journal"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CLOUDWATCH_NAMESPACE            = "TriageBot"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Bedrock Knowledge Base ID for the clinical-protocol corpus.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # The Knowledge Base index is built from the institution's
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # triage protocols (Schmitt-Thompson Adult, Schmitt-Thompson
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Pediatric, or institutional adaptations) plus the clinical-
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # decision-rule reference content, with metadata filters for
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # protocol_id, protocol_version, decision_point_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # pediatric_vs_adult, special_population_flags, and
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # effective_date.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m KNOWLEDGE_BASE_ID               = "KB_PLACEHOLDER_ID"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Bedrock Guardrail for restricted-topic filtering. Configure
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # in the Bedrock console with restricted topics for diagnosis-
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # attempted, treatment-recommendation-attempted, drug-
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # prescription-attempted, and off-protocol-clinical-claim at
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # minimum. Pin to a specific version, not DRAFT, in production.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m GUARDRAIL_ID                    = "GUARDRAIL_PLACEHOLDER_ID"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m GUARDRAIL_VERSION               = "1"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Deploy-time guardrail. Any blank resource name is a deploy-
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # time bug, not a runtime surprise.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m for _name, _value in [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("CONVERSATION_STATE_TABLE",        CONVERSATION_STATE_TABLE),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("CONVERSATION_METADATA_TABLE",     CONVERSATION_METADATA_TABLE),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("TOOL_CALL_LEDGER_TABLE",          TOOL_CALL_LEDGER_TABLE),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("DECISION_RECORD_TABLE",           DECISION_RECORD_TABLE),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("PROTOCOL_VERSION_REGISTRY_TABLE", PROTOCOL_VERSION_REGISTRY_TABLE),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("OUTCOME_CORRELATION_TABLE",       OUTCOME_CORRELATION_TABLE),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("TRIAGE_EVENT_BUS_NAME",           TRIAGE_EVENT_BUS_NAME),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("AUDIT_ARCHIVE_FIREHOSE_NAME",     AUDIT_ARCHIVE_FIREHOSE_NAME),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("DECISION_RECORD_BUCKET",          DECISION_RECORD_BUCKET),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("CLOUDWATCH_NAMESPACE",            CLOUDWATCH_NAMESPACE),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("KNOWLEDGE_BASE_ID",               KNOWLEDGE_BASE_ID),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("GUARDRAIL_ID",                    GUARDRAIL_ID),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ("GUARDRAIL_VERSION",               GUARDRAIL_VERSION),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     assert _value, f"{_name} must be set before deploying."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Versioning ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Every conversation turn carries the model version, the prompt
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # version, the Knowledge Base version, the Guardrail version,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # the active protocol version, the active clinical-rule
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # version, and the active disclosure-library version. This is
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # how a future audit reconstructs which versions produced any
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # given recommendation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m PROMPT_VERSION                  = "triage-bot-prompt-v1.0"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m AGENT_VERSION                   = "triage-agent-v1.0"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m DISCLOSURE_LIBRARY_VERSION      = "triage-disclosures-v1.0"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m INSTITUTION_ID                  = "acme-health-system"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m INSTITUTION_DISPLAY_NAME        = "Acme Health"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Model IDs ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Two model roles. Intent classification (presenting-symptom
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # identification and emergency screening) is a per-turn task
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # where a fast, cheap model handles routing; the orchestration
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # model handles the multi-step reasoning, the tool calls, and
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # the final response generation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # If your region requires cross-region inference, use the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # inference profile ID. TODO: verify the exact model IDs
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # available in your region and account; Bedrock model
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # availability evolves over time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m INTENT_CLASSIFICATION_MODEL_ID  = "anthropic.claude-3-5-haiku-20241022-v1:0"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ORCHESTRATION_MODEL_ID          = "anthropic.claude-3-5-sonnet-20241022-v2:0"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Pipeline Tuning ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Below this confidence on intent classification, ask a
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # clarifying question rather than routing to a specific
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # protocol that will produce a low-quality answer. Keep this
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # on the conservative side; better to clarify than to misroute.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m INTENT_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD     = Decimal("0.70")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Below this confidence on a parsed protocol answer, re-ask the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # question once before falling through to nurse-line escalation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ANSWER_CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD     = Decimal("0.65")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Care-level acuity ordering. Higher value = higher acuity. The
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # conservative-bias logic uses this ordering to pick the higher-
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # acuity recommendation when the protocol-driven and rule-
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # driven recommendations diverge.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CARE_LEVEL_ACUITY = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "self_care_at_home":     1,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "telehealth_visit":      2,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "primary_care_routine":  3,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "primary_care_24_48h":   4,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "primary_care_today":    5,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "urgent_care":           6,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "emergency_department":  7,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "call_911":              8,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Plain-English labels for care levels.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m CARE_LEVEL_LABEL = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "self_care_at_home":     "self-care at home",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "telehealth_visit":      "a telehealth visit",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "primary_care_routine":  "a routine primary-care visit",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "primary_care_24_48h":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "a primary-care visit in the next 1-2 days",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "primary_care_today":    "a same-day primary-care visit",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "urgent_care":           "an urgent-care visit today",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "emergency_department":  "an emergency-department visit",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "call_911":              "calling 911 right now",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Institution regulatory positioning: "informational" indicates
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # the deployment is positioned as informational with clinician
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # oversight in regulated edge cases; "registered_samd"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # indicates the deployment is registered as Software-as-a-
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Medical-Device with FDA SaMD post-market obligations. The
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # disclaimer language and the audit retention scale with this.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m INSTITUTION_REGULATORY_POSITION = "informational"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # --- Emergency-Screening Vocabulary ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # The continuous emergency-screening pipeline uses both keyword
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # detection (the demo) and a tuned classifier (production). The
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # vocabulary below covers the highest-yield emergency cues
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # across cardiac, neurological, respiratory, hemorrhagic,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # trauma, psychiatric, pediatric, and obstetric categories.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # In production each category is owned by clinical leadership
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # and reviewed against held-out emergency-presentation cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m EMERGENCY_VOCABULARY = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "cardiac": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "keywords": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "crushing chest pain", "elephant on my chest",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "chest pain radiating", "heart attack",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "urgency": "call_911",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "stroke": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "keywords": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "can't speak", "cant speak", "face drooping",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "weakness on one side", "sudden weakness",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "lost vision", "sudden vision loss",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "lost feeling in my arm",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "lost feeling in my leg",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "lost feeling in my legs",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "can't feel my legs", "cant feel my legs",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "urgency": "call_911",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "hemorrhagic": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "keywords": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "bleeding heavily", "won't stop bleeding",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "wont stop bleeding", "vomiting blood",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "coughing up blood", "blood in my stool",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "urgency": "call_911",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "anaphylaxis": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "keywords": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "throat closing", "can't breathe",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "cant breathe", "tongue swelling",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "anaphylaxis",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "urgency": "call_911",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "overdose": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "keywords": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "took too many pills", "overdose",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "took the whole bottle",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "urgency": "call_911",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "neurosurgical": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # Cauda equina pattern.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "keywords": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "lost bladder control",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "can't control my bladder",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "saddle numbness", "numbness in my groin",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "urgency": "call_911",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "psychiatric_crisis": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "keywords": [
